🧠 2946. Matrix Similarity After Cyclic Shifts
✨ Complete Notes (All 3 Approaches Combined — Crystal Clear)
🔹 Problem Summary
Given m × n matrix mat
Integer k
Perform operation k times:
Even rows → left shift
Odd rows → right shift

👉 Return true if final matrix == original

🔥 Core Optimization
k = k % n;
💡 Why?
After n shifts → row resets
Only remainder matters
🧠 Core Concept

❗ This problem is NOT about shifting
✔ It is about checking cyclic invariance (periodicity)

⚖️ APPROACH 1: Forward Mapping (Standard)
🔹 Idea:

Check:

"After shifting, what comes to index j?"

✔ Even row (LEFT shift)
mat[i][j] == mat[i][(j + k) % n]
✔ Odd row (RIGHT shift)
mat[i][j] == mat[i][(j - k + n) % n]
🧠 Thinking:
Left shift → element comes from right → +k
Right shift → element comes from left → -k
⚖️ APPROACH 2: Reverse Mapping (Your Approach 🔥)
🔹 Idea:

Check:

"Where does current element go?"

✔ Even row
mat[i][j] == mat[i][(j - k + n) % n]
✔ Odd row
mat[i][j] == mat[i][(j + k) % n]
🧠 Thinking:
Just reverse perspective
Still checking same cycle
⚖️ APPROACH 3: Simplified (Best Insight 🚀)
🔹 Idea:

Direction does NOT matter if array remains same

✔ Final Condition (for ALL rows)
mat[i][j] == mat[i][(j + k) % n]
🔥 Why this works?

Because:

Left shift by k  ⇄  Right shift by k

👉 If one keeps array same → other also does

🧩 Deep Insight (VERY IMPORTANT)

If:

mat[i][j] == mat[i][(j + k) % n]

Then automatically:

mat[i][j] == mat[i][(j - k + n) % n]

👉 Cyclic symmetry

🔍 Example
mat = [1,2,1,2], k = 2
Left shift → same
Right shift → same

✔ So direction irrelevant

❗ When Direction WOULD Matter
Scenario	Direction Matters?
Construct final matrix	✅ YES
Check equality	❌ NO
💻 Final Code (Cleanest — Approach 3)
class Solution {
public:
    bool areSimilar(vector<vector<int>>& mat, int k) {
        int m = mat.size();
        int n = mat[0].size();
        
        k %= n;

        for(int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
            for(int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
                if(mat[i][j] != mat[i][(j + k) % n])
                    return false;
            }
        }

        return true;
    }
};
⚡ Complexity
Type	Value
Time	O(m × n)
Space	O(1)
